Nov 7 2007	Amazing Resort with subpar Service	LOCATION: Excellent. You get the feeling that you are really in the middle of the desert and yet only 45 minutes away from the main parts of Dubai. Not the best location if you want to spend most of your time seeing the sites of Dubai. More for relaxation but there is a complimentary hotel shuttle that departs at 10:30AM and comes back in the evening time (one per day). BED/SHEETS/PILLOW: One of the most comfortable beds I have ever stayed in. Sheets were of high quality linens and pillows were down and perfect (I must admit I rarely give such high reviews of hotel beds).LIGHTING: Ok, not great in the bathroom and poor in the bedroom. One of the darkest rooms I have ever been in, but perhaps it’s part of the Arabic theme.BATHROOM/SHOWER: Bathroom was really nice, with a large tub and great shower with very strong pressure and consistent temperature that can get very hot.TOILETRIES: Excellent quality even though in unusual packaging.CLEANLINESS: The entire room and hotel common areas are exceptionally clean.A/C: Quietly kept our room very cool. Disliked that we could barely feel the air on our face.CLOSET SPACE: Enough space for 2 to unpack most items.STYLE OF ROOM: Exceptional! Arabic theme was great and the room had beautiful furnishings and décor. It was nice seeing the sand from our room. Supposedly all rooms are the same size, the only difference is the view. QUIET/LIGHT: Our room was very quiet at night yet sometimes could hear foot steps from the room above (it may be better to get an upper floor room, not sure how this would affect the view).FOOD: Good to excellent. We had 3 meals here and found the pool restaurant to be good and the Indian restaurant to be excellent (and I eat Indian food all the time).TV/INTERNET: Great size TV (not flat screen). Tons of English channels. Internet is wired in the room and is fast.SERVICE: This is where the hotel doesn’t impress. Fortunately everyone is nice but they just don’t deliver good service. There are tons of staff everywhere at the hotel but they don’t seem to help out the guests proactively. Expect to hunt them down for your request and to perhaps ask twice to get things done. COMMON AREA: Spectacular. It’s the perfect setting with the perfect hotel style to make this hotel special. The infinity pool is impressive as it appears to end in the sand dunes. The lobby area is also themed and very well done. Camels and falcons are available to entertain guests before sunset. TIPS:. Definitely go to the Indian restaurant. A cab ride to town will be from 70 to 100 Dhs (US$20+). If you want to eat the the Burj (sailboat hotel), make reservations before you leave on your trip, all the restaurants book early and there is only one at the top. Be sure to book lunch since we were told there is not much of a view at night. Perhaps book a few nights here and a few in the city. I strongly suggest staying here if you can deal with the fair service provided, the resort is truly amazing and a real desert experience.	
Nov 3 2007 	Big customer service problems	Jumeirah run a bunch of hotels around the world. That in itself should say &quot;good quality&quot; or &quot;sure bet&quot;. Bab Al Shams delivers on location and facilites, but staff managemnt sucks. Bab is a pretender.The staff are great - the staff managers are incompetent. Shangri-La Hotel in Oman has got its act together - when you pay top dollar you get awesome service, you don't need to wait too long for service by the pool, your restaurant waiters are observant, and check-in and check-out are a breeze.Bab Al Shams is a poor cousin. Nothing is quick or smooth. Pool service is pot-luck. Check-in and check-out are a trial. The whole operation is ad hoc. Depending on when you arrive at check-in or check-out, or at the pool or a restaurant, can determine how you are treated.The ultimate problem, therefore, is consistency. Bab Al Shams does not have it. It could be so awesome. You pay a lot for a stay at Bab, but it just doesn't deliver.Lift your game Bab. Lift your game.	
