Aug 5 2007 	A Comfortable Place to Stay in the Hot Desert	Booked two nights (July 30 – August 1, 2007) at the Spa Pampering Package rate of 700AED per night including one half hour massage. Having stayed the previous two nights at the Jumeirah Madinat Resort, we used the complimentary transportation to the desert resort. We were greeted at the vehicle and assisted inside where we were offered Arabian coffee and dates. Our check-in was fast and efficient and we were escorted to Room 222. The resort is spectacularly serene with area appropriate décor. It’s exactly what a desert spa should be. Our room did not have a great view or a balcony, but with the great bed and wonderful bath…who cares. The bed is the biggest I’ve ever slept in, about the size of two doubles. The sheets are cool and soft with lots of pillows. A nice window seat is perfect for reading (although the lights are dim). The bathroom is incredible with a large tub with little alcoves. The towels are perfect. The amenities are in the coolest little containers and I just had to take them. In the room was fresh fruit, a gift box of dates and complimentary bottled water. It was hard to leave the comfort of the room, but we were there to see the desert.It is so hot, even after the sun sets. But it is so beautiful, you just endure. We were set up by the pool first thing in the morning and we stayed put all day. As long as you stay in the pool, mostly underwater, in the shade from one of the thatched roofs, it’s not too hot. When it gets really bad, there’s a neat waterfall that showers you with chilled water. Trust me, you need it!We ordered bottled water and ice and enjoyed a tray of mixed mid-eastern appetizers from the pool bar. Around 4:30 PMout of nowhere, two camels came walking across the dunes. Their handler brings them over close to the pool. Guests can take complimentary rides, what a thrill. Later there’s a falcon show.We couldn’t bring ourselves to pay the 360AED for the dinner show. We did endure the intense heat and watch the sun set from the roof top bar and then went in the Italian restaurant for dinner.Again, we used the complimentary transportation back to the Jumeirah Beach Hotel. Our stay was perfect duration; we had arrived about 8 PM on Sunday evening, spent all day Monday and departed at 10:30AM on Tuesday. That gave one full day to enjoy the pool and the evening activities.The Bab Al Shams Desert Resort is a comfortable way to get a full appreciation of a visit to the desert, even in the heat of the summer. If you go to Dubai, make time to go.	
Jul 19 2007 	A nice but very average hotel	We stayed at Bab Al Shams after 5 nights at the Grosvenor.This hotel offers a completely different experience as it's an hour's drive from Dubai, in the desert.The hotel is built on a typical Arabian theme.The site itself is beautiful with rooms around courtyards and the pool area is great. There are jacuzzis in the swimming pool and a bar. I especially liked the shaded, seating areas in the pool where you can spend the time sheltering from the heat!Around 4 o'clock every day, there are free camel rides on the dunes, followed by a falconery display.You can also book to go out on the dunes on a 4x4 but unfortunately there weren't any spaces for when we were staying.The room was nice and we were upgraded to a suite. I did feel that they were a bit dingey as there wasn't much lighting but i suppose that was part of the Arabian style. Unfortunately, we constantly compared this hotel to the Grosvenor and it really did not even begin to match up. The food was fresh and good quality, but limited and the other restaurants and bars around the site were dead! We were the only people in them on both evenings.Bab Al Shams is a nice hotel but always felt empty. The only thing to do is the Al hadheerah restaurant which looks great fun (we didn't go) but a bit expensive.On both days we were there, busloads of German tourists would descend on the hotel in the late afternoon, which made us think that maybe the Bab Al Shams is used by tours just as an overnight stop-off for the Al Hadheerah experience.As with most of the Jumeirah places i visited in Dubai (Burj Al Arab, Wadi Water Park, Madinat Jumeriah, Mina Asalam, Jumeirah Beach hotel) the service and friendliness all felt a bit forced. This is noted when you are constantly asked to fill in the customer satisfaction forms and see the questions about whether you were greeted with a smile, blah, blah, blah.Anyway, in conclusion, what doesn't please one person could be a perfect holiday for another. This was not my type of hotel. The Arabian-style hotels in Dubai seem too fake as they have been purpose built. I prefer the Grosvenor as it doesn't want to be anything it's not. It depends what you want.Saying that, Bab Al Shams is a five-star hotel so obviously if you stay here you are not going to find anything that awful. As the choice of hotels in Dubai is so great, and the reason why most people want to go there is for the absolute luxury of the hotels i wanted to underline that this is not one of the best choices.If you like a VERY quiet location and poolside. This place is an absolute haven.	
Jul 7 2007 	A Palace in the Desert	A bit over an hour’s drive from Dubai into the desert, this place can only be described as an Arabian Palace in the desert. There is a free shuttle bus from Dubai at 6.30pm and another free shuttle bus from the resort to Dubai in the mornings. Driving up the private road, lit by flames all the way to the entrance, you feel as if you have entered another world. A warm welcome by the well trained staff, our bags were whisked away and we were settled into our beautiful room before we knew it. The whole place was all Arabian style décor and lovely artwork adorned the walls. There were robes, slippers, fresh dates, fruit and cold water. The bed was enormous. Bigger than a king size and the pillows were just sensational. We were just so exhausted and all we wanted to do was to have a shower, have something to eat and a good nights sleep. We did just that and had a light meal at the Al Forsan restaurant, which was where we had breakfast for the next 3 days. Breakfast was a feast. The breakfast room looks out over a croquet court and in the distance you see the Palm trees and just sand, sand and more sand. Now the food here was nothing less than 7 star. There was so much we did not know where to start. We decided we were going to have something different everyday. We tried camel milk and loved it. We had tiny bowls of beautifully presented crème caramels, creamed camel rice, all decorated in little pieces of mango and strawberry. Some of the fruit, we had never eaten before, but it was all very sweet and tasted fantastic. There was a whole Japanese section, a huge section of Danish pastries croissants and cakes. Eggs done every way imaginable and a chef to whip you up anything you wanted. We decided to go for waffles one morning and there were about 10 different toppings to put on and my partner asked the chef for cream as we did not see it on the buffet. Next minute the chef ran out the back and came back with fresh cream in a bowl and whisked the cream. He said we don’t like to put cream out. They like to do it fresh for everyone individually. So our breakfasts were fantastic each morning. The pools are amazing. There is one huge pool that goes on forever. Another one the same size, is a heated spa and you can swim over the bubbles and just lay there and be gently massaged under the watchful eye of the 4 lifeguards, who sit there all day under an umbrella. The pool attendant, Thomas was amazing. He looked after us so well. He would see us arrive at the pool, offer us drinks and towels. Nothing was too much trouble and always smiling and happy. All of the staff greeted us with happy smiles and could not do enough for us.We tried all of the restaurants, the same thing, service was unbelievable, and food was excellent.The Al Hadeerah Restaurant just had to be the icing on the cake for us. It is a traditional outside Arabian restaurant about 300 metres from the resort, so you can walk through the desert path, lit by flames or they will take you by buggy. As you arrive at the restaurant there is a huge red carpet you walk down and either side is lit up with flames and fairy lights. Standing to the left of you are 6 beautiful Arabian horses and their riders and on the right are barrels of fresh fruit and vegetables and wagons with big pumpkins piled high.You are welcomed by a beautiful hostess and head waiter all in traditional dress and taken to our seat. The buffet, which is all outside is nothing short of amazing food stations that have different varieties of food. They have lamb on a spit, a huge seafood and steak BBQ and you can choose your fish or meat and they will cook it for you. There are huge prawns and lobsters, two stations just with shish kebabs being bbq'd and a vegetable wok in the middle. Tables and tables of salads fruit and deserts and an ice cream stand. For starters, you are brought bowls of dips, salads and bread. There is an Arabian band playing on a big stage and above the stage on the sand dunes there are camels being led over the sand dunes. After the camels, come the beautiful Arabian horses and their riders and they put on a great exhibition of riding and stunts. We settled back into our comfy little lounge and just enjoyed the whole thing. A wonderful singer, an Egyptian dancer and of course the fabulous belly dancer kept us entertained, so in between the buffet and the entertainment we almost forget to go to the arena next door for the camel rides, market and Falcon exhibition.After having my arm painted in a lovely design with Henna paint we head off home for a lovely walk back to the resort.Next day we decided to have a massage in the Satori Spa and also booked the steam room which we found we could have to ourselves. Beautiful. 3 days was not enough at the Bab AL Sham Resort. We booked this as a last treat to relax after spending 6 weeks in Europe racing around, seeing sites and having a great time. We just wish we would have booked a week. Bab Al Sham truly is a Palace in the Desert.	
Jun 22 2007 	nice hotel but iffy service	We arrived at this hotel at 9am on Sunday 3rd June for a one week stay.We had specifically booked for June as the brochure price incuded free half board.Our room was not ready on arrival so we were ushered off to have breakfast (which we were charged for). We then sat around the pool and our room was eventually ready at around 11.30am.The room itself ws decorated in what I would describe as a &quot;minimalist Arab style&quot; but nevertheless very pleasing especially given the range of toiletries available (including a shaving kit for you men!)Whilst we had received confirmation of free half board from our travel agent , me being me wanted to check whether we could eat in all restaurants (excluding the Al Hadheerah) on this free basis. When we got to reception they told us that we weren't booked on half board at all!!! 30 minutes of haggling later and we sorted this out (and were told that if we ate at &quot;le Dune&quot; or &quot;Masala&quot; we would be limited to 150 dirhams credit per person for food). However on checking out, our bil included the cost of all meals! Again, 30 minutes of discussions sorted this out. The pool areas, restaurants and bars were very nice (although we never ate at the Al Hadheerah as we thought it was a bit expensive for what you got). Most of the waiting on staff were competent (except for &quot;lazy&quot; Haleem who I am going to name and shame) but the reception desk staff seemed completely uninterested and ignorant. I would suggest that they go on a customer services course. Overall the service was inconsistent from excellent to very poor.Now to our final day....We had already told the reception staff we would be checking out at 11am as we had been down earlier to check our (incorrect) bill. However on arriving at the reception area for checkout (and having had to carry our own cases because the porter never turned up) we were swamped by a group of 77 Germans, a tour group who were checking out en masse at the very same time. It took us 35 minutes to reach the reception desk which made us late for our transfer back to the airport.We would happily have checked out earlier if we had been told about the mass checkout at 11, or one of the staff could even have come and sorted this out in our room. But no, the only response we got from a member of staff was &quot;you will just have to wait in the queue like everyone else!&quot;. This is not what I would expect from a 5 star hotel. With this in mind and taking into account our overall experience at the Bab al Shams, I would class this hotel as a decent 4 star or a poor 5 star. The service was definitely not what I had been lead to believe I would get in Dubai (and definitely not what I have experienced in other 5 star hotels across the world).Finally I would suggest that you take booking details confirming all of the options you have chosen and check your bill!	
May 21 2007 	Absolutely amazing	Where do I start with a review on this hotel. My husband booked a holiday as a surprise for my 30th bday and when I found out and read the reviews on this hotel I was to say the least a bit dubious about going but it was all booked so off we went for a week. We only returned today (20th May 2007) and the first thing I want to do is stand up for this hotel and let people know exactly what it is like. We arrived early on sunday morning and we were unable to check into our room but in fairness it was 6am..breakfast starts every morning at 6.30 so we were able to go there and waste a bit of timing while waiting for our room. We got checked into our room by 9.30am and from then on I have absolutely nothing but amazing things to say about the place. The staff could not have done enough to help us. The first evening when we arrived back to our hotel room there was a chocolate bday cake waiting for us with &quot;Happy Birthday&quot; on it as they knew it was my bday from the booking. We ate between Al Forsan and Le Dune for our entire stay and both were brilliant. The buffet in Al Forsan gives you the choice to go for an all you can eat for 165Dirham or just two courses for 115 which I thought was great because most buffets only offer all or nothing. The pizzeria was my favourite though as the pizzas are made right in front of you and the chef interacts with the customers and was only too happy to cater for my awkward palate. On completion of our meal we decided to move out to the rooftop bar and the staff insisted on carrying out the wine and water and wouldn't let us do it at all. Then when it comes to the room service that was out of this world. Our bed linen was changed every single day...we got laundry cleaned for us and on calling service one at 9.45 we had someone at our door to collect it before 10am and then it was returned all completed by 6.30 that evening for 16dirham for my blouse...for that service you can't go wrong. Then the room services come into the rooms in the evenings aswell and will do a full clean again...light a nightlight in the bath to set the atmosphere put down mats on each side of the beds along with turning down the sheets leaving chocolates or dates...oh and you get fresh fruit every morning left in your room...all your toiletries are layed out nice and neatly in the bathroom..any clothes would be folded..I can't say one entire bad thing about it at all. We even were in the room one day until after 2 and the lady still came in when we left even though we had really missed the morning clean as we were in the room.The staff around the pool were also so friendly...we were never waiting for anything for any length of time. They were busy from the thursday till the saturday and still they were very efficient. We were greated by our names after the first day or two by most of the staff that seem to work 6 days a week there.We also used the spa and again it is brilliant and well worth it...the massages are the same price as you would get in any high class spa.We went to Al Hadera on one night which is the arabian themed restaurant that is out in the desert and adjacent to this hotel. We went because it was right beside us and felt that it would be a shame to miss it. This is probabably if I was to complain would be the only thing...it is a bit overpriced for what you get. Again it is 350dirhams per adult and that is for the show and all you can eat buffet but drinks are extra. Go if you want to just say you have been there but again in hine sight we probably would have had just as enjoyable a night in the hotel.So all in all it was a brilliant holiday the hotel does not deserve the reviews it has got on this site but again they are other peoples opinions..try it you will definitely go back I know we will..	
