Oct 24 2006 	Fantastic but the 'activities' let it down.....	This is a top quality hotel in the middle of the desert. The pool is spectacular and the view of the dunes at sunset is lovely.The bar is now finished and is a wonderful place to relax, drink, try the shishas etc. The service is excellent. We spent many hours in there watching the sun set and staring up at the stars.The new Indian restaurant is now open - we went on their 2nd night - the food is excellent and well worth a visit. We let the waitress recommend some dishes and we weren't disappointed. One of the best indian meals we've ever had.The only negative thing to say about the hotel is the choice and quality of the 'activities' they offer. We wanted to drive over the dunes in a 4x4 or bune buggy. The only activity they offered was being a passenger in an open top jeep driving over the small dunes round the hotel. This didn't sound very exciting so we opted for the camel safari instead. The actual 'safari' was basically sitting on a camel for an hour whilst it is lead over the dunes. Our guide didn't speak English and clearly didn't enjoy his job much! He basically listened to his ipod for the whole safari and didn't once turn round to see if we were OK. This seemed disappointing considering that it cost £25 each.Nevertheless this is a lovely place to stay and well worth spending a few nights at. Be warned though - it is hot!! It was 44 degrees in October so we spent most of our time in the pool!	
Oct 15 2006 	Desert Heaven	Just returned from a four day break . It was superb . This was our first visit and we can advise that the rooftop bar is now complete and the service was excellent.This place really is in the middle of the desert and it's unlikely there is anywhere in the world with a pool / pools quite like this where you can chill out and virtually touch the sand dunes .The hotel is perfect for relaxation and more relaxation. A four night stay was perfect and the hotel is ideal for those visiting Dubai and wanting a twin centre holiday with one of the beach or city hotels or those working in the middle east looking for a romantic break . A tip for when to visit , the hotel gets a little busier Thursday night and Friday day when Dubai high fliers come to the hotel for a night away and to relax with the family,. To be honest though the place never feels really crowded like European hotels .It is true that you will be eating at one of the hotels restaurants at present there is a fine Pizza place , an a la carte restaurant , a desert restaurant and coming soon an Indian . The rooftop bar also serves good snack food . Lik emost quality hotels the food is not cheap but it isn't astronomical like other remote 5 stars and cost the same as a decent UK restaurant . We found the service to be really good and always with a smile and the guests we came across often gave the staff a really tough time with their odd requests .The hotel rooms are large with great A\C and large bathrooms with very deep baths . This hotel is unique and well worth a visit to relax in the sunshine for a few days . We had great fun.	
Sep 1 2006 	Still a few rough edges	Stayed for 3 nights in August and found it a wonderful hotel. Pool and room excellent. Even at well over 100 F.degrees outside ( 45 degrees Celsius) the rooms were well air condtioned and pleasant to chill out in. Hotel food very good and although it is expensive and a tourist trap don't miss going to the desert restaurant one evening. The hotel's new roof top bar and restaurants are due to open in the next few weeks and this will further enhance the hotel. Only down side was the service which was generally slow but particularly so in the current roof top bar. In August it is low season and the hotel was not even 50% occupied but still we had to wait every evening at least 10 minutes before even being offered a drinks menu (without apology. ) Also loud discussions between the Italian manageress and the bar staff about rota/shift systems on two occaisions did not exactly contribute to a quite/relaxed atmosphere in the bar .Taxi ride back to Dubai airport takes approx. 40 minutes and costs Dhrms. 120.Highly recommend this hotel for a short break in combination with the Madinat Mina al Salam in Dubai. Get to Bab al Shams soon while it is still surrounded by desert. Dubai is expanding so fast that one day soon the hotel will be in a Dubai suburb!!	
Aug 31 2006 	Chill Out zone in the heat of the Desert	Absolutely amazing place - an oasis of peace and quiet right in the middle of the Dubai desert.Won't be suitable for everyone - no hectic nightlife scene, little for kids on site and not much in the way of local sightseeing but if it's a quiet getaway you are after for a few days with your other half it's absolutely perfect.Rooms are Arabian rustic in style but large and comfortable. They are also spotlessly clean. They are spread out across the resort - which resembles an old walled fort (although being Dubai it's actually about 18 months old!!!) - and come in a mixture of with/without balconys and suites.The pool area is absolutely outstanding - split level with infinity views it was both beatifully designed and relaxing. It's also so large you feel it is your own personal space.At the moment there is limited eating areas (pool and restaurant and lobby bar area with an off-site outdoor dining/entertainment facility) but I understand work is well on the way to add additional restaurants on the complex. The food was good however throughout the complex and the breakfast was large buffet style with omelette/waffle stations for on-the-spot service.There is also a very pleasant rooftop bar where you can sit out until the very early hours and enjoy the night sky - and perhaps a shisha too! Very nice indeed and very relaxing!Overall, prices were quite reasonable at this resort and perhaps slightly lower than in Dubai city/Jumeirah beach hotels being run by the same group.Would we go back? Yes, in an instant	
Jul 30 2006 	Amazing Romantic Stay	Whilst staying at the Jumeriah Beach Resort and Burj Al Arab for our Honeymoon we were offered the chance to 'swap' some days of our 14 night stay for Bab Al Shams. It turned our to be an excellent suggestion. It was more rustic and traditional compaired to that of the 'shiny' Jumeriah Beach and Burj. We had drinks on the roof top and visited the Santorini Spa. Staff we excellent and the atmosphere was really nice. Highly recommended and Arabian Hospitality at its finest.	
Jul 23 2006	A pool with a view	Haved just returned from a 4 night stay at The 'Babs', originaly visited in October of last year when the construction work to enlarge the pool was taking place, on this occassion dissapointed with the noise and the size of pool, however glad we returned as the improvements have made this one of the most intresting and largest pools in any Dubai Hotel. The layout is spectacular and the view across the gardens towards the desert is something to be seen. The number of chairs and umberellas far out number demand and you can find a quite corner easily. The pool staff are ,as at any Jumeirah property exceptional and all the usual cold towels fruit skewers and huge buckets of ice arrive complimentary with a smile. The only down side to this hotel is the dull and dreary restaurant where you have to take buffet brekfast and evening meals, however in a few months time a new larger restaurant overlooking the desert is due to open together with an Indian and an Italian this will make this a true 5 star resort. in the meantime, room service menu is good and the quality of food as good as if served in the restaurant. We hope to re-visit early next year and to enjoy the improvements. Highly reccomend this hotel to couples looking for tranquility and style at a very affordable rate, worth staying as an add on to a Dubai hotel to either unwind at the beining or end of your holiday. Can also highly recommend the Summerhouses at Dar al Masyaf at The Madinat Jumeirah, pure induldgence in a dream location.	
Jun 13 2006	surpassed expectations.......	My husband and I stayed at Babs Al Sham resort for 2 days last week and had a fantastic time. I was initially reluctant to venture there, having read previous reviews related to delays in rooms being ready. However we decided to to give it a go and was suprised that when we arrived at 11.30 am we were immediately given the keys to our room (normal check in is at 4.00pm!!)The hotel was very clean, efficient and the staff extremely friendly. The pools were amazing and I could quite happily have stayed there a weekMy only criticism was that we asked to book a table at the retaurant for the first evening. We were asked whether we wanted to go to the one in the hotel or the open air 'desert' one. We went for the latter and wes slightly amazed to find ourselves in a buffet style Arabian themed restaurant with belly dancers, camels etc. The food was good but it wasn't the romantic place I was expecting . I feel that this should have been explained to us before bookingThis however will certainly not put us off staying at the hotel again, we intend to return on our next visit ti Dubai. (although we'll give restaurant a miss)	
May 22 2006	Mixed feelings	Bab al Shams looks to be set in an ideal environment, the perfect hideaway in appearance.To be fair, the rooms are nice, large and well furnished. The problem is the service.I have been living in Dubai for more than 6 months now and Bab al Shams ranks amongst the worst service level for a 5 star hotel. Check-in at 4:30 (rooms not ready), artificial smile from most of the staff, clumsy gestures, etc... The desert restaurant is to avoid. It is expensive and the atmosphere is disapointing. The entertainers are not at the level you would expect for this kind of resort. Dubai has lot more to offer. The food is good though. We had visitors from abroad and wanted to please them by booking a couple of days in the desert...the whole experience was disapointing. On top of that, it is no longer in the middle of nowhere, civilization is not far...	
May 7 2006	good break	We stayed at the resort for 2 days and 3 nights and it was a good break from the busy dubai life.Well we were greeted by the hospitable staff only to find out that our room wasnt ready and would take another half an hour or so.I was abit upset because we were accompanied by our little 1 1/2 yr old daughter and wanted to go and unwind in our room.The room was very nice and tastefully decorated .The pool was fabulous!!! My baby loved the pool.  The food is avearge.I would say they desperately need to increase their menu beacuse you run out of choices on the second day of your stay.Al Hadeera is good fun and entertainment although definitely over priced but you get to experience the core of the Arab culture here. The staff is friendly and helpful. The children play area is not too big but is good enough to keep them busy for an hour or two. Over all i would say that there is scope for alot of improvement where as food and entertainment is concerned but its definitely good enough for a short getaway.Very relaxing and serene environment.	
